<h1>Ellipse Calculator</h1>
<p>Calculations at an ellipse. An ellipse is a closed, oval curve in which =
the sum of the two distances of any point on the curve from the focal point=
s is always the same.<br>
Enter the two semi axes and choose the number of decimal places. Then click=
 Calculate. The semi-major axis is the distance between center and one poin=
t on the ellipse furthest away from this. The semi-minor axis is the distan=
ce between center and one point on the ellipse closest to this. They are up=
right to each other. The linear eccentricity is the distance of the focal p=
oints to the center. The circumference is calculated with an approximation =
formula (second approximation of Srinivasa Ramanujan), which is very exact =
up to =CE=B5&lt;0.9 and has a maximal error of 0.04% at  =CE=B5=3D1. An exa=
ct calculation can be done with elliptic integrals (Jacobi integrals), whos=
e values can be taken from tables.<br>
c<sub>B</sub> is an about 7 times better estimation, expending the second a=
pproximation of Ramanujan, by J=C3=BCrgen Beck. This is based on an astroid=
 approximation and is not verified yet.</p><br>
